'''Andri Steinþór Björnsson''' (born 11 January 1973) is a clinical psychologist and an associate professor of psychology at the [[University of Iceland]].  In addition to his work on [[Body dysmorphic disorder|body dysmorphic syndrome]],<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Body dysmorphic disorder|journal = Dialogues in Clinical Neuroscience|date = 2010-01-01|issn = 1294-8322|pmc = 3181960|pmid = 20623926|pages = 221–232|volume = 12|issue = 2|first = Andri S.|last = Bjornsson|first2 = Elizabeth R.|last2 = Didie|first3 = Katharine A.|last3 = Phillips}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Age at onset and clinical correlates in body dysmorphic disorder|journal = Comprehensive Psychiatry|date = 2013-10-01|issn = 1532-8384|pmc = 3779493|pmid = 23643073|pages = 893–903|volume = 54|issue = 7|doi = 10.1016/j.comppsych.2013.03.019|first = Andri S.|last = Bjornsson|first2 = Elizabeth R.|last2 = Didie|first3 = Jon E.|last3 = Grant|first4 = William|last4 = Menard|first5 = Emily|last5 = Stalker|first6 = Katharine A.|last6 = Phillips}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Body dysmorphic disorder|journal = Dialogues in Clinical Neuroscience|date = 2010-06-01|issn = 1294-8322|pmc = 3181960|pmid = 20623926|pages = 221–232|volume = 12|issue = 2|first = Andri S.|last = Bjornsson|first2 = Elizabeth R.|last2 = Didie|first3 = Katharine A.|last3 = Phillips}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = The Clinical Course of Body Dysmorphic Disorder in the Harvard/ Brown Anxiety Research Project (HARP)|journal = The Journal of Nervous and Mental Disease|date = 2011-01-01|issn = 0022-3018|pmc = 3667613|pmid = 21206248|pages = 55–57|volume = 199|issue = 1|doi = 10.1097/NMD.0b013e31820448f7|first = Andri S.|last = Bjornsson|first2 = Ingrid|last2 = Dyck|first3 = Ethan|last3 = Moitra|first4 = Robert L.|last4 = Stout|first5 = Risa B.|last5 = Weisberg|first6 = Martin B.|last6 = Keller|first7 = Katharine A.|last7 = Phillips}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Anxiety Disorders: Bjornsson, Andri - Expertscape.com|url = http://www.expertscape.com/au/anxiety+disorders/Bjornsson,+Andri|website = www.expertscape.com|accessdate = 2016-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = C-2 Andri Bjornsson|url = http://www.congress.is/eabct/c-2_andri_bjornsson.aspx|website = www.congress.is|accessdate = 2016-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Patients who loathe appearance often get better, but it could take years {{!}} News from Brown|url = https://news.brown.edu/articles/2011/01/bdd|website = news.brown.edu|accessdate = 2016-01-05}}</ref> he has hosted a series of radio programs on science and the scientific method broadcast by [[RÚV]] [e. The Icelandic National Broadcasting Service], as well as editing and writing books on science aimed at the general public.{{Citation needed|date=January 2016}}

== Education ==
Following his Bachelors and master's degrees<ref>{{Cite journal|title = The Effects of Experiential Avoidance and Rumination on Depression among College Students|journal = International Journal of Cognitive Therapy|date = 2010-12-01|issn = 1937-1209|pages = 389–401|volume = 3|issue = 4|doi = 10.1521/ijct.2010.3.4.389|first = Andri|last = Bjornsson|first2 = Gregory|last2 = Carey|first3 = Monika|last3 = Hauser|first4 = Alexis|last4 = Karris|first5 = Vyga|last5 = Kaufmann|first6 = Erin|last6 = Sheets|first7 = W. Edward|last7 = Craighead}}</ref> in psychology at the University of Iceland in 1998 and 2003, Björnsson attended the University of Colorado at Boulder where he wrote a master´s thesis on depression amongst college students and received his PhD degree in 2009 based on his doctoral thesis, the topic of which was a randomized clinical trial employing cognitive behavioral group therapy.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Specific and Non-Specific Factors in the Cognitive-Behavioral Group Therapy of College Students with Social Anxiety Disorder: A Randomized Clinical Trial|url = http://www.bookdepository.com/Specific-Non-Specific-Factors-Cognitive-Behavioral-Group-Therapy-College-Students-with-Social-Anxiety-Disorder-Andri-Bjornsson/9781243630896|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref> He worked as a clinical intern at McLean Hospital/Harvard Medical School where he developed an interest in [[body dysmorphic disorder]], and joined a post-doctoral fellowship at the Warren Alpert Medical School of [[Brown University]] where he participated in clinical studies of body dysmorphic disorder.

== Writing ==
In addition to his published work on body dysmorphic syndrome and other research in psychology,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Panic symptoms increase steadily, not acutely, after stressful event|url = http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2011-06/bu-psi062011.php|website = EurekAlert!|accessdate = 2016-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Andri Bjornsson - Google Scholar Citations|url = https://scholar.google.is/citations?user=atQB6d8AAAAJ&hl=en&oi=ao|website = scholar.google.is|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = Avoidant Personality Disorder|publisher = John Wiley & Sons, Inc.|date = 2010-01-01|isbn = 9780470479216|doi = 10.1002/9780470479216.corpsy0105/abstract|language = en|first = Andri S.|last = Bjornsson|doi-broken-date = 2018-08-28}}</ref> Björnsson has written or edited two books aimed at a general audience on the history of  science and the scientific method,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Er vit í vísindum?  {{!}} Háskólaútgáfan|url = http://haskolautgafan.hi.is/er_vit_i_visindum|website = haskolautgafan.hi.is|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Vísindabyltingin {{!}} Háskólaútgáfan|url = http://haskolautgafan.hi.is/visindabyltingin|website = haskolautgafan.hi.is|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref> and recently co-edited a book honoring the life and work of Vilhjálmur Rafnsson.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Af lífi - Greinasafn handa Vilhjálmi Rafnssyni {{!}} Háskólaútgáfan|url = http://haskolautgafan.hi.is/af_lifi_greinasafn_handa_vilhjalmi_rafnssyni|website = haskolautgafan.hi.is|accessdate = 2016-01-04}}</ref>

== Current work ==
Björnsson joined the faculty of the University of Iceland in 2011 as an associate professor, and was promoted to his current position as associate professor in 2014. His current research focuses on general anxiety disorders, social anxiety disorders, and panic disorders, with particular interest in obsessive and compulsive behaviour within these disorders,<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Posttraumatic stress disorder in African Americans: a two year follow-up study|journal = Psychiatry Research|date = 2014-12-15|issn = 1872-7123|pmc = 4351655|pmid = 25086766|pages = 376–383|volume = 220|issue = 1–2|doi = 10.1016/j.psychres.2014.07.020|first = Carlos I.|last = Pérez Benítez|first2 = Nicholas J.|last2 = Sibrava|first3 = Laura|last3 = Kohn-Wood|first4 = Andri S.|last4 = Bjornsson|first5 = Caron|last5 = Zlotnick|first6 = Risa|last6 = Weisberg|first7 = Martin B.|last7 = Keller}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Barking up the wrong tree in attentional bias modification? Comparing the sensitivity of four tasks to attentional biases|journal = Journal of Behavior Therapy and Experimental Psychiatry|date = 2015-09-01|issn = 1873-7943|pmid = 25665514|pages = 9–16|volume = 48|doi = 10.1016/j.jbtep.2015.01.005|first = Ólafía|last = Sigurjónsdóttir|first2 = Sólrún|last2 = Sigurðardóttir|first3 = Andri S.|last3 = Björnsson|first4 = Árni|last4 = Kristjánsson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Two-year course of generalized anxiety disorder, social anxiety disorder, and panic disorder with agoraphobia in a sample of Latino adults|journal = Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology|date = 2014-12-01|issn = 1939-2117|pmc = 4197105|pmid = 24731232|pages = 1186–1192|volume = 82|issue = 6|doi = 10.1037/a0036565|first = Andri S.|last = Bjornsson|first2 = Nicholas J.|last2 = Sibrava|first3 = Courtney|last3 = Beard|first4 = Ethan|last4 = Moitra|first5 = Risa B.|last5 = Weisberg|first6 = Carlos I. Pérez|last6 = Benítez|first7 = Martin B.|last7 = Keller}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Do Obsessions and Compulsions Play a Role in Social Anxiety Disorder?|journal = Harvard Review of Psychiatry|pages = 1|date = 2013-11-08|issn = 1465-7309|pmid = 24216613|doi = 10.1097/HRP.0000000000000009|first = Andri S.|last = Bjornsson|first2 = Katharine A.|last2 = Phillips}}</ref> in addition to his work on body dysmorphic disorder.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Changes in body image and dieting among 16-19-year-old Icelandic students from 2000 to 2010|journal = Body Image|date = 2014-09-01|issn = 1873-6807|pmid = 24995408|pages = 364–369|volume = 11|issue = 4|doi = 10.1016/j.bodyim.2014.05.006|first = Gudrun|last = Ingolfsdottir|first2 = Bryndis Bjork|last2 = Asgeirsdottir|first3 = Thrudur|last3 = Gunnarsdottir|first4 = Andri Steinthor|last4 = Bjornsson}}</ref>

== Radio programs ==
In 1998, Björnsson hosted a seven part series on the "Most important scientific theories of our time" broadcast by RÚV [e. The Icelandic National Broadcasting Service], aimed at educating the general public on topics including the [[Big Bang|big bang theory]], the [[theory of evolution]], and the [[Plate tectonics|theory of plate tectonics]].

