{{Infobox anatomy | Name = Theca interna | Latin = tunica interna thecae folliculi | Image = | Caption = | Image2 = | Caption2 = | Precursor = | System = | Artery = | Vein = | Nerve = | Lymph = }} '''Theca interna''' cells express [[Luteinizing hormone/choriogonadotropin receptor|receptors]] for [[luteinizing hormone]] (LH) to produce [[androstenedione]], which via a few steps, gives the [[granulosa]] the precursor for [[estrogen]] manufacturing.
After rupture of the mature [[ovarian follicle]], the theca interna cells differentiate into the [[theca lutein cell]]s of the [[corpus luteum]]. Theca lutein cells secrete [[androgen]]s<ref name=iups/> and [[progesterone]]. Theca lutein cells are also known as small luteal cells.<ref name=iups>[http://www.bioeng.auckland.ac.nz/physiome/ontologies/female_repro_system/cells.php The IUPS Physiome Project --> Female Reproductive System - Cells] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091210133027/http://www.bioeng.auckland.ac.nz/physiome/ontologies/female_repro_system/cells.php |date=December 10, 2009 }} Retrieved on Nov 9, 2009</ref>
